antis develops a new theory of norm change and identifies its stages, including redefinition (involving domestic political deliberations) and constructive norm substitution (in multilateral institutions). He deftly takes some of the most controversial new developments in military technologies and embeds them in international relations theory. The case evidence he presents suggests that periods of change are underway across numerous different issue areas.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 23. Jul 2020) 0aInternational law. 0aMilitary weaponsxTechnological innovationsxUnited States. 0aMilitary weaponsxTechnological innovationszUnited States. 0aNational securityxTechnological innovationsxUnited States. 0aNational securityxTechnological innovationszUnited States. 0aTechnology and international relations. 4aU.S. foreign policy. 4aconstructive norm substitution. 4acontestation. 4ainternational norms. 4anorm change. 4anuclear weapons. 4areconnaissance satellites. 4aspace technology. 4atechnology innovations. 4aunmanned aerial vehicles. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Security (National & International).2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUP Complete eBook-Package 2016z978311070397940uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978080479984340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780804799843423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780804799843.jpg  a978-3-11-070397-9  SUP Complete eBook-Package 2016b2016  aGBV-deGruyter-alles